{"title_page": "Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Rodr\u00edguez y Cos", "text_new": "'''Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Rodr\u00edguez y Cos''' was a [[Mexico|Mexican]] writer who promoted [[Positivism]] in the country. He was born in [[Tulancingo]], [[Hidalgo (state)|Hidalgo]], Mexico in 1823, and although he began his studied to be a doctor, he had to leave university due to finances. He worked as a teacher and began to write, and became associated with Positivist writers such as [[Vicente Hugo Alcar\u00e1z]] and [[Manuel Guill\u00e9n]]. His master work is considered to be epic poem ''El An\u00e1huac'', published in 1852. Another popular poem is ''La Revoluci\u00f3n francesa''. He also wrote plays such as the opera ''Cuauht\u00e9moc'' and translated a number of plays and other works from French and Italian into Spanish. Rodr\u00edguez y Cos died in [[Mexico City]] in 1899.<ref name=\"rincones\">{{cite book |editor1-first=Victor Manuel |editor1-last=Jimenez Gonzalez |title=Hidalgo: Gu\u00eda para descubrir los encantos del estado |trans-title=Hidalgo: Guide to discover the charms of the state |year=2010 |publisher=Editorial Oc\u00e9ano de Mexico SA de CV |location=Mexico City |language=Spanish |isbn=978-607-400-319-2 |page=15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodriguez Y Cos, Jose Maria}}\n[[Category:1823 births]]\n[[Category:Mexican male writers]]\n[[Category:1899 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Tulancingo]]\n[[Category:19th-century Mexican educators]]\n[[Category:Mexican translators]]\n[[Category:19th-century Mexican poets]]\n\n\n{{Mexico-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Rodr\u00edguez y Cos''' was a [[Mexico|Mexican]] writer who promoted [[Positivism]] in the country. He was born in [[Tulancingo]], [[Hidalgo (state)|Hidalgo]], Mexico in 1823, and although he began his studied to be a doctor, he had to leave university due to finances. He worked as a teacher and began to write, and became associated with Positivist writers such as [[Vicente Hugo Alcar\u00e1z]] and [[Manuel Guill\u00e9n]]. His master work is considered to be epic poem ''El An\u00e1huac'', published in 1852. Another popular poem is ''La Revoluci\u00f3n francesa''. He also wrote plays such as the opera ''Cuauht\u00e9moc'' and translated a number of plays and other works from French and Italian into Spanish. Rodr\u00edguez y Cos died in [[Mexico City]] in 1899.<ref name=\"rincones\">{{cite book |editor1-first=Victor Manuel |editor1-last=Jimenez Gonzalez |title=Hidalgo: Gu\u00eda para descubrir los encantos del estado |trans-title=Hidalgo: Guide to discover the charms of the state |year=2010 |publisher=Editorial Oc\u00e9ano de Mexico SA de CV |location=Mexico City |language=Spanish |isbn=978-607-400-319-2 |page=15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodriguez Y Cos, Jose Maria}}\n[[Category:1823 births]]\n[[Category:Mexican male writers]]\n[[Category:1899 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Tulancingo]]\n[[Category:19th-century Mexican educators]]\n[[Category:Mexican translators]]\n[[Category:19th-century Mexican poets]]\n\n\n{{Mexico-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Rodr%C3%ADguez_y_Cos"}
{"title_page": "James Whitshed (died 1789)", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish politician}}\n'''James Whitshed''' (c.1716\u20131789) was an Irish politician who sat in the British [[House of Commons]] for 29 years from 1754 to 1783.  \n \nWhitshed was the son of James Whitshed of Dublin and his wife Grace Dillon. He entered [[Trinity College, Dublin]] on 10 February 1733. He married Frances Bathurst daughter of [[Allen Bathurst, 1st Earl Bathurst|Allen, 1st Earl Bathurst]] and widow of [[William Wodehouse]] MP on 5 December 1738. Later he married Frances Enery daughter of Thomas Enery of Bawnboy, county Cavan.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/whitshed-james-c1716 | title =Whitshed, James (b. c. 1716), of Hampton Court, Mdx.| publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 9 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhitshed was MP for [[Wicklow Borough (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Wicklow]] in the [[Parliament of Ireland]] from 1747 to 1760. He became connected with the Leicester House faction through his father-in-law, Lord Bathurst and before the [[1747 British general election|general election of 1747]] and was included in a list by Dr Ayscough of \u201cpersons to be brought into Parliament by his Royal Highness, who are not able to bring in themselves\u201d.  He did not stand until the [[1754 British general election|1754 general election]] when he was returned unopposed as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[St Ives (UK Parliament constituency)|St Ives]] on the Praed interest. In [[1761 British general election|1761]] he was returned as MP for [[Cirencester (UK Parliament constituency)|Cirencester]] after a contest on the Bathurst interest. He was re-elected at Cirencester in [[1768 British general election|1768]], [[1774 British general election|1774]] and [[1780 British general election|1780]]. In May 1783 he resigned to allow Lord Bathurst's son, [[Henry Bathurst, 3rd Earl Bathurst|Lord Apsley]] who had come of age to sit. There is no record of any speech by him during his 29 years in the House.<ref name = HOP/>\n\nWhitshed had residences at Hampton Court and at New Burlingston Street, London. He died in February 1789. There is a commemorative tablet to him in the church of [[St James, Piccadilly]] on the North vestibule wall.<ref>[http://www.sjp.org.uk/memorials.html St James Piccadilly memorials]</ref>  Under the terms of his will, his cousin [[James Hawkins-Whitshed]] was to assume the name and arms of Whitshed in addition to his own, and legislation was passed in the British and Irish parliaments in 1791 to allow exemplification of his will.<ref>[http://www.qub.ac.uk/ild/?func=simple_search&search_type=name&search=true&search_string=0995&&session_from=1692&session_to=1800 Irish Legislation Database]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[John Bristow]]\n | before2 =  [[Samuel Stephens (senior)|Samuel Stephens]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[St Ives (UK Parliament constituency)|St Ives]]\n | years = [[1754 British general election|1754]]\u2013[[1761 British general election|1761]]\n | with  =  [[George Hobart, 3rd Earl of Buckinghamshire|Hon. George Hobart]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Humphrey Mackworth Praed]]\n | after2 = [[Sir Charles Hotham-Thompson, 8th Baronet|Colonel Charles Hotham]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Benjamin Bathurst (1711\u20131767)|Hon. Benjamin Bathurst]]\n | before2 = [[John Dawnay, 4th Viscount Downe|Hon. John Dawnay]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Cirencester (UK Parliament constituency)|Cirencester]]\n | years = [[1761 British general election|1761]]\u20131783\n | with  =  [[John Dawnay, 4th Viscount Downe|Hon. John Dawnay]] 1761-1768\n| with2  =  [[Estcourt Creswell]]  1768-1774\n| with3  =  [[Samuel Blackwell]]  1774-1783\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Henry Bathurst, 3rd Earl Bathurst|Lord Apsley]]\n | after2 = [[Samuel Blackwell]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitshed, James}}\n[[Category:1789 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1754\u20131761]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1761\u20131768]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1768\u20131774]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1774\u20131780]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1780\u20131784]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish politician}}\n'''James Whitshed''' (c.1716\u20131789) was an Irish politician who sat in the British [[House of Commons]] for 29 years from 1754 to 1783.  \n \nWhitshed was the son of James Whitshed of Dublin and his wife Grace Dillon. He entered [[Trinity College, Dublin]] on 10 February 1733. He married Frances Bathurst daughter of [[Allen Bathurst, 1st Earl Bathurst|Allen, 1st Earl Bathurst]] and widow of [[William Wodehouse]] MP on 5 December 1738. Later he married Frances Enery daughter of Thomas Enery of Bawnboy, county Cavan.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/whitshed-james-c1716 | title =Whitshed, James (b. c. 1716), of Hampton Court, Mdx.| publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 9 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhitshed was MP for [[Wicklow Borough (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Wicklow]] in the [[Parliament of Ireland]] from 1747 to 1760. He became connected with the Leicester House faction through his father-in-law, Lord Bathurst and before the [[1747 British general election|general election of 1747]] and was included in a list by Dr Ayscough of \u201cpersons to be brought into Parliament by his Royal Highness, who are not able to bring in themselves\u201d.  He did not stand until the [[1754 British general election|1754 general election]] when he was returned unopposed as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[St Ives (UK Parliament constituency)|St Ives]] on the Praed interest. In [[1761 British general election|1761]] he was returned as MP for [[Cirencester (UK Parliament constituency)|Cirencester]] after a contest on the Bathurst interest. He was re-elected at Cirencester in [[1768 British general election|1768]], [[1774 British general election|1774]] and [[1780 British general election|1780]]. In May 1783 he resigned to allow Lord Bathurst\u2019s son, [[Henry Bathurst, 3rd Earl Bathurst|Lord Apsley]] who had come of age to sit. There is no record of any speech by him during his 29 years in the House.<ref name = HOP/>\n\nWhitshed had residences at Hampton Court and at New Burlingston Street, London. He died in February 1789. There is a commemorative tablet to him in the church of [[St James, Piccadilly]] on the North vestibule wall.<ref>[http://www.sjp.org.uk/memorials.html St James Piccadilly memorials]</ref>  Under the terms of his will, his cousin [[James Hawkins-Whitshed]] was to assume the name and arms of Whitshed in addition to his own, and legislation was passed in the British and Irish parliaments in 1791 to allow exemplification of his will.<ref>[http://www.qub.ac.uk/ild/?func=simple_search&search_type=name&search=true&search_string=0995&&session_from=1692&session_to=1800 Irish Legislation Database]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[John Bristow]]\n | before2 =  [[Samuel Stephens (senior)|Samuel Stephens]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[St Ives (UK Parliament constituency)|St Ives]]\n | years = [[1754 British general election|1754]]\u2013[[1761 British general election|1761]]\n | with  =  [[George Hobart, 3rd Earl of Buckinghamshire|Hon. George Hobart]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Humphrey Mackworth Praed]]\n | after2 = [[Sir Charles Hotham-Thompson, 8th Baronet|Colonel Charles Hotham]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Benjamin Bathurst (1711\u20131767)|Hon. Benjamin Bathurst]]\n | before2 = [[John Dawnay, 4th Viscount Downe|Hon. John Dawnay]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Cirencester (UK Parliament constituency)|Cirencester]]\n | years = [[1761 British general election|1761]]\u20131783\n | with  =  [[John Dawnay, 4th Viscount Downe|Hon. John Dawnay]] 1761-1768\n| with2  =  [[Estcourt Creswell]]  1768-1774\n| with3  =  [[Samuel Blackwell]]  1774-1783\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Henry Bathurst, 3rd Earl Bathurst|Lord Apsley]]\n | after2 = [[Samuel Blackwell]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitshed, James}}\n[[Category:1789 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1754\u20131761]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1761\u20131768]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1768\u20131774]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1774\u20131780]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1780\u20131784]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Whitshed_(died_1789)"}
{"title_page": "Charles Powlett, 5th Duke of Bolton", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2008}}\n[[File:Coat of arms of The Most High, Puissant, and Noble Prince Charles Powlett, Duke of Bolton, Marquis of Winchester, Earl of Wiltshire, Baron St. John of Basing, Premier Marquis of England, by Sir William Segar and Joseph_Edmondson, 1764.jpg|thumb|Coat of arms of 'The Most High, Puissant, and Noble Prince Charles Powlett, Duke of Bolton, Marquis of Winchester, Earl of Wiltshire, Baron St. John of Basing, Premier Marquis of England', by Sir [[William Segar]] and [[Joseph Edmondson]], 1764.]]\n\n'''Charles Powlett, 5th Duke of Bolton''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|KB|PC}} (c. 1718 \u2013 5 July 1765), styled '''Marquess of Winchester''' from 1754 to 1759, was a British soldier, nobleman and [[British Whig Party|Whig]] politician. He was the eldest son of [[Harry Powlett, 4th Duke of Bolton]] and Catherine Parry.\n\nEducated at [[Winchester College|Winchester]], he joined the [[British Army]] and became a [[Lieutenant Colonel|lieutenant-colonel]] in 1745. Powlett was a [[Groom of the Bedchamber]] to [[Frederick, Prince of Wales]] from 1749 until the Prince's death in 1751. He had been promoted [[Lieutenant General|lieutenant general]] by 12 March 1752, when he was made a [[Order of the Bath|KB]].\nUpon the succession of his father to the Dukedom in December 1754, he became known as '''Marquess of Winchester''',<ref>[[George Edward Cokayne]], ed. [[Vicary Gibbs (St Albans MP)|Vicary Gibbs]], ''[[The Complete Peerage]]'', vol. II, p. 214, The St Catherine Press, London, 1912</ref> and he left his seat at [[Lymington (UK Parliament constituency)|Lymington]] to succeed his father in [[Hampshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Hampshire]]. He would remain member for that county until his succession as Duke of Bolton in 1759. On 22 December 1758, he was sworn of the [[Privy Council of Great Britain|Privy Council]].\n\nOn 5 July 1765, Bolton died by suicide - shooting himself in the head with a pistol in his house in [[Grosvenor Square]]; \"nobody knows why or wherefore,\" wrote Horace Walpole, \"except that there is a good deal of madness in the blood\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Letters of Horace Walpole, earl of Orford |last=Walpole |first=Horace |authorlink=Horace Walpole|year=1844 |publisher=Lea & Blanchard |location= |volume=1 |page=133 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c7Y_AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover |accessdate=30 June 2011}}</ref> Unmarried, he left most of his fortune to his illegitimate daughter, Jean Mary Browne-Powlett (c.1751\u20131814), who married [[Thomas Orde-Powlett, 1st Baron Bolton]]. He was succeeded in the Dukedom by his brother [[Harry Powlett, 6th Duke of Bolton|Harry]].\n\n==Grosvenor Square==\n[[Lord Nassau Powlett]], son of 2nd Duke of Bolton, had No 24 (formerly no 21), 1735\u201338, and [[Charles Powlett, 3rd Duke of Bolton|the 3rd duke]], and then his widow, had No 1, 1753\u201355. The 5th duke had No. 37 (formerly no 32) from 1759\u201365. For him it was extensively altered c. 1761\u20135 by [[John Vardy]], (demolished in 1934).<ref>'In 1781 there was one water closet, hung with green flock paper and equipped with what was called a 'Mahogany Watercloset with Bason and Handles Compleat', situated on the ground floor. The library on the same floor, which had an out-of-order wind-dial over the chimneypiece, was hung with green gilt-bordered flock paper. Above, the curtains, hangings and upholstery of the two drawing-rooms were all of crimson damask, and the two Wilton carpets each covered 'the whole Floor'.'</ref> Following the 5th duke Bolton the lease holders or occupiers were the 3rd [[Augustus FitzRoy, 3rd Duke of Grafton|Duke of Grafton]], Prime Minister, 1765; 4th [[Charles Bennet, 4th Earl of Tankerville|Earl of Tankerville]], 1769\u201379; [[House of Alvensleben|Baron Alvensleben]], Hanoverian Minister, c. 1780\u201392; 6th [[Harry Powlett, 6th Duke of Bolton|Duke of Bolton]], 'for tenants', c. 1793\u20135.<ref>'Information kindly supplied by Mr. Roger White from MSS. at Hackwood: R.I.B.A. Drawings Collection, John Vardy, G4/4/1': via ''Survey of London: Volume 40, the Grosvenor Estate in Mayfair'', Part 2 (The Buildings). London County Council, London, 1980.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Lymington (UK Parliament constituency)|Lymington]]\n | with   = [[Sir Harry Burrard, 1st Baronet, of Walhampton|Sir Harry Burrard]]\n | before = [[Lord Nassau Powlett]]\n | before2= [[Sir Harry Burrard, 1st Baronet, of Walhampton|Sir Harry Burrard]]\n | after  = [[Sir Harry Burrard, 1st Baronet, of Walhampton|Sir Harry Burrard]]\n | after2 = [[Adam Drummond]]\n | years  = [[1741 Lymington by-election|1741]]\u2013[[1754 British general election|1754]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Hampshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Hampshire]]\n | years  = [[1754 British general election|1754]]\u2013[[1759 Hampshire by-election|1759]]\n | with   = [[Alexander Thistlethwayte]]\n | before = [[Harry Powlett, 4th Duke of Bolton|Lord Harry Powlett]]\n | before2= [[Alexander Thistlethwayte]]\n | after  = [[Alexander Thistlethwayte]]\n | after2 = [[Henry Bilson-Legge]]\n}}\n{{s-hon}}\n{{s-bef | rows=3 | before=[[Harry Powlett, 4th Duke of Bolton|The 4th Duke of Bolton]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Lieutenant of the Tower of London]] | years=1754\u20131760}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[George Paulet, 12th Marquess of Winchester|George Paulet]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Lord Lieutenant of Hampshire]] | years=1758\u20131763}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[James Brydges, 3rd Duke of Chandos|Marquess of Carnarvon]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Vice-Admiral of Dorset]] and [[Vice-Admiral of Hampshire|Hampshire]] | years=1759\u20131765}}\n{{s-vac | next=[[Harry Powlett, 6th Duke of Bolton|The 6th Duke of Bolton]]}}\n{{s-reg|en}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Duke of Bolton]] | before=[[Harry Powlett, 4th Duke of Bolton|Harry Powlett]] | years=1759\u20131765 | after=[[Harry Powlett, 6th Duke of Bolton|Harry Powlett]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bolton, Charles Powlett, 5th Duke of}}\n[[Category:1710s births]]\n[[Category:1765 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Army generals]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1741\u20131747|Winchester, Charles Powlett, Marquess of]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1747\u20131754|Winchester, Charles Powlett, Marquess of]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1754\u20131761|Winchester, Charles Powlett, Marquess of]]\n[[Category:Knights Companion of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Lord-Lieutenants of Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies|Winchester, Charles Powlett, Marquess of]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Nobility who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Suicides by firearm in England]]\n[[Category:People educated at Winchester College]]\n[[Category:Paulet family|Charles]]\n[[Category:Dukes of Bolton|15]]\n[[Category:British politicians who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:British military personnel who committed suicide]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2008}}\n[[File:Coat of arms of The Most High, Puissant, and Noble Prince Charles Powlett, Duke of Bolton, Marquis of Winchester, Earl of Wiltshire, Baron St. John of Basing, Premier Marquis of England, by Sir William Segar and Joseph_Edmondson, 1764.jpg|thumb|Coat of arms of 'The Most High, Puissant, and Noble Prince Charles Powlett, Duke of Bolton, Marquis of Winchester, Earl of Wiltshire, Baron St. John of Basing, Premier Marquis of England', by Sir [[William Segar]] and [[Joseph Edmondson]], 1764.]]\n\n'''Charles Powlett, 5th Duke of Bolton''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|KB|PC}} (c. 1718 \u2013 5 July 1765), styled '''Marquess of Winchester''' from 1754 to 1759, was a British soldier, nobleman and [[British Whig Party|Whig]] politician. He was the eldest son of [[Harry Powlett, 4th Duke of Bolton]] and Catherine Parry.\n\nEducated at [[Winchester College|Winchester]], he joined the [[British Army]] and became a [[Lieutenant Colonel|lieutenant-colonel]] in 1745. Powlett was a [[Groom of the Bedchamber]] to [[Frederick, Prince of Wales]] from 1749 until the Prince's death in 1751. He had been promoted [[Lieutenant General|lieutenant general]] by 12 March 1752, when he was made a [[Order of the Bath|KB]].\nUpon the succession of his father to the Dukedom in December 1754, he became known as '''Marquess of Winchester''',<ref>[[George Edward Cokayne]], ed. [[Vicary Gibbs (St Albans MP)|Vicary Gibbs]], ''[[The Complete Peerage]]'', vol. II, p. 214, The St Catherine Press, London, 1912</ref> and he left his seat at [[Lymington (UK Parliament constituency)|Lymington]] to succeed his father in [[Hampshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Hampshire]]. He would remain member for that county until his succession as Duke of Bolton in 1759. On 22 December 1758, he was sworn of the [[Privy Council of Great Britain|Privy Council]].\n\nOn 5 July 1765, Bolton died by suicide - shooting himself in the head with a pistol in his house in [[Grosvenor Square]]; \"nobody knows why or wherefore,\" wrote Horace Walpole, \"except that there is a good deal of madness in the blood\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Letters of Horace Walpole, earl of Orford |last=Walpole |first=Horace |authorlink=Horace Walpole|year=1844 |publisher=Lea & Blanchard |location= |volume=1 |page=133 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c7Y_AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover |accessdate=30 June 2011}}</ref> Unmarried, he left most of his fortune to his illegitimate daughter, Jean Mary Browne-Powlett (c.1751\u20131814), who married [[Thomas Orde-Powlett, 1st Baron Bolton]]. He was succeeded in the Dukedom by his brother [[Harry Powlett, 6th Duke of Bolton|Harry]].\n\n==Grosvenor Square==\n[[Lord Nassau Powlett]], son of 2nd Duke of Bolton, had No 24 (formerly no 21), 1735\u201338, and [[Charles Powlett, 3rd Duke of Bolton|the 3rd duke]], and then his widow, had No 1, 1753-55. The 5th duke had No. 37 (formerly no 32) from 1759-65. For him it was extensively altered c. 1761\u20135 by [[John Vardy]], (demolished in 1934).<ref>'In 1781 there was one water closet, hung with green flock paper and equipped with what was called a 'Mahogany Watercloset with Bason and Handles Compleat', situated on the ground floor. The library on the same floor, which had an out-of-order wind-dial over the chimneypiece, was hung with green gilt-bordered flock paper. Above, the curtains, hangings and upholstery of the two drawing-rooms were all of crimson damask, and the two Wilton carpets each covered 'the whole Floor'.'</ref> Following the 5th duke Bolton the lease holders or occupiers were the 3rd [[Augustus FitzRoy, 3rd Duke of Grafton|Duke of Grafton]], Prime Minister, 1765; 4th [[Charles Bennet, 4th Earl of Tankerville|Earl of Tankerville]], 1769\u201379; [[House of Alvensleben|Baron Alvensleben]], Hanoverian Minister, c. 1780\u201392; 6th [[Harry Powlett, 6th Duke of Bolton|Duke of Bolton]], 'for tenants', c. 1793\u20135.<ref>'Information kindly supplied by Mr. Roger White from MSS. at Hackwood: R.I.B.A. Drawings Collection, John Vardy, G4/4/1': via ''Survey of London: Volume 40, the Grosvenor Estate in Mayfair'', Part 2 (The Buildings). London County Council, London, 1980.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Lymington (UK Parliament constituency)|Lymington]]\n | with   = [[Sir Harry Burrard, 1st Baronet, of Walhampton|Sir Harry Burrard]]\n | before = [[Lord Nassau Powlett]]\n | before2= [[Sir Harry Burrard, 1st Baronet, of Walhampton|Sir Harry Burrard]]\n | after  = [[Sir Harry Burrard, 1st Baronet, of Walhampton|Sir Harry Burrard]]\n | after2 = [[Adam Drummond]]\n | years  = [[1741 Lymington by-election|17